[HackerRank - Java if else](https://www.hackerrank.com/challenges/java-if-else)

In this challenge, we test your knowledge of using if-else conditional statements to automate decision-making processes. An if-else statement has the following logical flow:

![if-then-else-diagram-image](https://s3.amazonaws.com/hr-challenge-images/13689/1446563087-4ec019a919-332px-If-Then-Else-diagram.svg.png)

Source: [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_%28computer_programming%29)

### Task

Given an integer, **n**, perform the following conditional actions:

If **n** is odd, print ***Weird***
If **n** is even and in the inclusive range of **2** to **5**, print ***Not Weird***
If **n** is even and in the inclusive range of **6** to **20**, print ***Weird***
If **n** is even and greater than **20**, print ***Not Weird***
Complete the stub code provided in your editor to print whether or not **n** is weird.

### Input Format

A single line containing a positive integer, **n**.

### Constraints

```bash 
1<= n <= 100
```

### Output Format

Print ***Weird*** if the number is weird; otherwise, print ***Not Weird***.

### Sample Input 0

```bash
3
```

### Sample Output 0

```bash
Weird
```

### Sample Input 1

```bash
24
```

### Sample Output 1

```bash
Not Weird
```

### Explanation

Sample Case 0: **n = 3**
**n** is odd and odd numbers are weird, so we print ***Weird***.

Sample Case 1: **n ==24**
**n > 20** and **n** is even, so it isn't weird. Thus, we print ***Not Weird***.

### Solving the challenge

First let's check the base code provided to us.

```Java
import java.io.*;
import java.math.*;
import java.security.*;
import java.text.*;
import java.util.*;
import java.util.concurrent.*;
import java.util.regex.*;

public class Solution {
     private static final Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

     public static void main(String[] args) {
         int N = scanner.nextInt();
         scanner.skip("(\r\n|[\n\r\u2028\u2029\u0085])?");

         scanner.close();
     }
}

```
Let's start by identifying whether **N** is even or odd, we do this using the **%** operator which returns the remainder of the division, if the remainder of the division is equal to 0 (zero), this means that the value is even, if not, the value is odd.

```Java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Solution {
     private static final Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

     public static void main(String[] args) {

         int N = scanner.nextInt();
         scanner.skip("(\r\n|[\n\r\u2028\u2029\u0085])?");

         boolean isOdd = N % 2 != 0 ? true : false;

         scanner.close();
     }
}
```

Now, let's go to the conditionals. If **N** is odd, we should print ***Weird***

```Java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Solution {
     private static final Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

     public static void main(String[] args) {

         int N = scanner.nextInt();
         scanner.skip("(\r\n|[\n\r\u2028\u2029\u0085])?");

         boolean isOdd = N % 2 != 0 ? true : false;

         if (isOdd) {
             System.out.println("Weird");
         }

         scanner.close();
     }
}
```

If **N** is not odd and **N** is greater than 2 and **N** is less than 5, we should print ***Not Weird***


```Java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Solution {
     private static final Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

     public static void main(String[] args) {

         int N = scanner.nextInt();
         scanner.skip("(\r\n|[\n\r\u2028\u2029\u0085])?");

         boolean isOdd = N % 2 != 0 ? true : false;

         if (isOdd) {
             System.out.println("Weird");
         } else if (!isOdd && N > 2 && N < 5) {
             System.out.println("Not Weird");
         }

         scanner.close();
     }
}
```

If **N** is not odd and **N** is greater than 6 and **N** is less than 20, we must print ***Weird***

```Java
import java.util.Scanner;

